helor of Arts degree from [[Asbury University|Asbury College]] in [[Wilmore, Kentucky]], a Master of Divinity degree from [[Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary]] in [[Fort Worth, Texas]], and a Doctor of Ministry degree from [[Luther Rice Seminary]] in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jodyhice.com/JodyBio.php|title=Bio of Jody Hice|publisher=|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHice first served as senior pastor of Bethlehem First Baptist Church, until April 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bethlehemfbc.org|title=Jody Hice Pastors First Baptist Church of Bethlehem, GA|publisher=}}</ref> in [[Bethlehem, Georgia]]. In addition, he served as first vice president of the Georgia Baptist Convention (2004\u201305) and Professor of Preaching at [[Luther Rice Seminary]]. Hice served as senior pastor at The Summit Church, a Southern Baptist church, in [[Loganville, Georgia]] from 2011 until December 2013, when he stepped down to run for office.\n\n==''The Jody Hice Show''==\nDuring the battle between the ACLU and Barrow County, Georgia, regarding the public display of the Ten Commandments in the County Courthouse, Hice was asked by a local radio station to provide weekly updates and to address various other issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jodyhice.com|title=The Jody Hice Show|publisher=jodyhice.com|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom that weekly program a daily show, ''Let Freedom Ring'', which was originally heard on [[WJBB (AM)|WIMO]] 1300 AM, [[Bethlehem, Georgia]] was born. The show is heard on about 400 stations,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jodyhice.com/currentStations.php|title=Current Stations Airing The Jody Hice Show|publisher=|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> the show focuses on Constitutional, moral, and religious liberty issues.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2014 election===\nThe Congressional Seat for Georgia's 10th Congressional District opened up when the sitting representative, [[Paul Broun]], announced his bid for U.S. Senate in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Killough|first1=Ashley|title=Georgia Rep. Paul Broun to run for Senate|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2013/02/06/georgia-rep-paul-broun-to-run-for-senate/|publisher=CNN|date=February 6, 2013}}</ref> Hice was the second to formally enter the race on April 15, 2013, citing government spending as his foremost concern.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Galloway|first1=Jim|title=Jody Hice enters GOP race to replace Paul Broun|url=http://www.ajc.com/weblogs/political-insider/2013/apr/15/jody-hice-enters-gop-race-replace-paul-broun/|agency=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 15, 2013}}</ref> Hice was soon joined by 5 other candidates, leading to [[primary election]] of 7 for the open seat. Hice placed first in the primary on May 20, 2014 with 34% of the vote, followed closely by his run-off opponent Mike Collins who won 33% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/51345/132192/en/summary.html|website=GA Secretary of State Page|title=Ga Election Results|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWith no candidate winning 50% of the vote, a run-off campaign was issued between the top two candidates, Hice and Mike Collins. The close race quickly grew heated amid accusations of campaign sign theft from both sides and reports of supporters being harassed at debates.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cochran|first1=Kelsey|title=Hice, Collins campaign heats up with reports of sign thefts, 'shenanigans'|url=http://onlineathens.com/election/2014-07-19/hice-collins-campaign-heats-reports-sign-thefts-shenanigans|publisher=Athens Banner-Herald|date=July 20, 2014}}</ref> Hice ultimately won the run-off, grabbing 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Georgia \u2013 Summary Vote Results|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2014/by_state/GA_US_House_0722.html?SITE=CSPANELN&SECTION=POLITICS|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHice faced a Democratic opponent in November election, which he won (66.52%-33.48%) in a GOP wave on November 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covnews.com/section/1/article/56815|title=covnews.com, Jody Hice wins seat in U.S. House, November 4, 2014|publisher=covnews.com|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|'''Committee on Armed Services''']]\n**Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities\n**Subcommittee on Strategic Forces \n*'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n**Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources\n**Subcommittee on Water, Power and Oceans\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n**Vice Chairman of the Subcommittee on Government Operations\n**[[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on National Security|Subcommittee on National Security]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hice.house.gov/biography/committees.htm|title=Committees : Congressman Jody Hice|website=hice.house.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* '''[[Freedom Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=What is the House Freedom Caucus, and who's in it?|author=|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/10/20/house-freedom-caucus-what-is-it-and-whos-in-it/|format=|publisher=Pew research center|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Veterinary Medicine Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members of the Veterinary Medicine Caucus|author=|url=https://schrader.house.gov/committees/veterinary-medicine-caucus.htm|format=| publisher=Veterinary Medicine Caucus |date=|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n=== Economic issues ===\n\nHice supports a [[balanced budget amendment]].<ref name=\"OTIBudget\"/>\n\nHice supports auditing the [[federal reserve]] and its activities around mortgages. He co-sponsored the [[Federal Reserve Transparency Act]].<ref name=\"OTIBudget\">{{cite web|title=Doug Collins on Budget & Economy|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Doug_Collins_Budget_+_Economy.htm|website=On the Issues|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHice favors [[tax reform]] and voted in support of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=25 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> He claims the new legislation creates a \"competitive and fair tax system.\" He says it will create an improved economy, more opportunities, and \"keep more money in the pockets of hardworking families and individuals.\" He also believes \"It will also encourage American businesses to keep their jobs and revenue here, and our job creators will once again be competitive internationally.\"<ref name=\"Yeomans122317\">{{cite web|last1=Yeomans|first1=Curt|title=POLITICAL NOTEBOOK: Gwinnett's Republican representatives in Washington celebrate tax bill passage|url=http://www.gwinnettdailypost.com/local/political-notebook-gwinnett-s-republican-representatives-in-washington-celebrate-tax/article_182cd456-d5fd-5f50-856e-f11d22b41f33.html|website=Gwinnett Daily Post|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nHice is [[pro-life]]. He opposes [[abortion]]s being used for race or sex selection. He believes that life begins at fertilization or cloning. He opposes family planning assistance that includes abortion.<ref name=\"OTIAbortion\">{{cite web|title=Doug Collins on Abortion|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Doug_Collins_Abortion.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Interest group ratings===\n\nHice has a \"D\" rating from marijuana legalization advocacy organization [[NORML]] for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related issues.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Georgia Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/georgia|website=NORML|accessdate=December 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT issues===\nHice opposes gay marriage.<ref>Jody Hice is likely headed to Congress, Sean Sullivan, 23 July 2014, Washington Post</ref> According to [[Right Wing Watch]], Hice compared homosexuality to alcoholism and opposed a ban on gay conversion therapy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sarlin|first1=Benjy|title=Anti-Islam pastor Jody Hice wins Georgia primary|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/ultra-conservative-jody-hice-wins-ga-10-primary|publisher=MSNBC}}</ref>\n\n===Religious issues===\n\nIn September 2008, Hice was one of 33 pastors across America who participated in \"Pulpit Freedom Sunday\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineathens.com/stories/100608/ele_340689679.shtml|title=Jody Hice Returns To National Spotlight With Presidential Endorsement|publisher=onlineathens.com|accessdate=February 2, 2018}}</ref> an effort that challenged an [[Internal Revenue Service]] code threatening churches and pastors with loss of [[tax-exempt]] status and criminal behavior if they address [[Johnson Amendment|political issues from the pulpit]]. In that sermon, Hice endorsed [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John McCain]] for [[President of the United States|President]]. The IRS never publicly responded to the event, and Pulpit Freedom Sunday has since grown to include over 450 churches.<ref name=\"MSN-IRS-R\">{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/30391105/|title=Churches await IRS response after protest|date=April 24, 2009|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=2009-05-20}}</ref>\n\nHice has argued that Christians have been \"tricked\" into a \"false belief\" in separation of church and state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/content/rep-jody-hice-church-state-separation-encourages-corruption|title=Rep. Jody Hice: Church-State Separation Encourages Corruption|work=Right Wing Watch|publisher=People for the American Way}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.foxnews.com/2015/06/18/congressman-jody-hice-christians-tricked-into-believing-separation-of-church-and-state/ |title=Congressman Jody Hice: Christians 'Tricked' Into Believing Separation Of Church And State|work=Fox News Radio|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150621013904/http://radio.foxnews.com/2015/06/18/congressman-jody-hice-christians-tricked-into-believing-separation-of-church-and-state|archivedate=2015-06-21}}</ref>\n\nNational media outlets have drawn attention to Hice's views on Islam regarding his book, ''A Call to Reclaim America'', in which he claims that Islam is not only a religion, but a geo-political structure and is therefore not deserving of First Amendment protection.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bookman|first1=Jay|title=Is the First Amendment only for Christians?|url=http://www.ajc.com/weblogs/jay-bookman/2014/jun/23/first-amendment-only-christians|publisher=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=June 23, 2014}}</ref> Hice, in his book ''It's Now or Never'', also quoted former U.S. general [[William G. Boykin|Jerry Boykin]] as stating that there is a [[Muslim Brotherhood]] plot to take over the United States.<ref>Hice, Jody. ''It's Now or Never'', pg. 155</ref>\n\n===Women's rights===\nIn a 2004 interview with the ''[[Athens Banner-Herald]]'', the largest newspaper in Hice's district, Hice stated that a woman had to be \"within the authority of her husband\" if she wanted to run for public office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onlineathens.com/stories/021504/new_20040215071.shtml|title=Influx of women into government hits home|first=Beth|last=Hatcher|website=onlineathens.com|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n* [http://www.hice.house.gov/ Congressman Jody Hice] official U.S. House website\n* [http://www.jodyhice.com Jody Hice for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Jody_Hice_%5BR-10%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|jodyhice}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=H001071 | votesmart=122246 | fec=H0GA07125 | congress=jody-hice/2237 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Georgia\n| district=10 \n| before=[[Paul Broun]] \n| start=2015\n}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Glenn Grothman]] <br>R-[[Wisconsin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=332nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[French Hill (politician)|French Hill]]<br>R-[[Arkansas]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{GA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hice, Jody}}\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Baptists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Critics of Islam]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Asbury University alumni]]\n[[Category:Opposition to Islam in the United States]]\n[[Category:Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary alumni]]\n[[Category:Luther Rice University alumni]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]"}]}}}}